Who is likely to churn?¶

You are competing for a job as a business analyst working for a mobile phone company like Verizon, Mint Mobile, or AT&T. As part of the interview process, you have been tasked with exploring which customers are likely to “churn”.

Customer churn, also known as customer attrition, occurs when customers stop doing business with a company or stop using a company’s services. The company uses an annual valuation of $1200 per customer so if a customer churns (i.e. switches service) they are out a considerable sum of money.

The company believes...

  • Churn is influenced by the network speed (5G or 4G LTE) and the phone model
  • Customers who opt for paperless billing are less likely to churn

Some Expectations¶

  • Think about the business problem and how your analysis can address the problem
  • Make sure any chart you create has: title, x & y axis labels, and a description of why someone would care to look at it
  • Make sure you spend time understanding what your code does.

Task 2. Cleansing & Profiling (Part I)¶

Our dataset contains in following varibales:

  • monthly_minutes: Monthly usage in minutes
  • customer_service_calls: # of calls to customer services
  • streaming_minutes: Monthly streaming in minutes
  • total_billed: Total bill amount in $
  • prev_balance: Previous balance statement
  • late_payments: # of late payments
  • ip_address_asn: IP address
  • phone_area_code: Phone area code
  • customer_reg_date: Customer registration date
  • email_domain: Customer email
  • phone_model: Phone model
  • billing_city: Billing city
  • billing_postal: Billing zip code
  • billing_state: Billing state
  • partner: A partnering company who helped initiate the phone contract
  • phone_service: phone service
  • multiple_lines: multiple lines
  • streaming_plan: streaming plan
  • mobile_hotspot: mobile hotspot
  • wifi_calling_text: wifi calling text
  • online_backup: online backup
  • device_protection: device protection
  • number_phones: # of phones obtained
  • contract_code: code of the contract with the company
  • currency_code: payment currency
  • maling_code: mailing code
  • paperless_billing: opt for paperless billing
  • payment_method: payment method
  • customer_id: customer id
  • billing_address: full billing address
  • gender: gender
  • network_speed: network speed
  • senior_citizen: if the customer is a senior citizen

# For Loop Automation: Fire up a for loop that creates a histogram for each variable using sns.histplot(), with hue='churn'.
for column in numeric_vars:
  #column = 'monthly_minutes, customer_service_calls, streaming_minutes, total_billed, prev_balance, late_payments, number_phones'
  plt.figure(figsize=(10,3))
  sns.histplot(data=df_churn, x=column, hue='churn', bins=30)
  plt.title(f"histogram of {column}")
  plt.xlabel(f"column: {column}")
  plt.ylabel("count")
  plt.show();

Your Findings:

  • Majority of phone usage (number of minutes used to call and to stream) is captured from 10,000 to 30,000 and has a unimodal shape. It looks quite symmetric and has a center of roughly 20,000 minutes.
  • Churn does not seem to be a huge issue in the numeric variable columns. It seems to have two types of patterns for previous balance and total billed where churn is present and at its highest at the lower values. While for monthly minutes and minutes streamed is at its highest and present at the higher values.
  • It seems quite common for there to be 4 to 6 phones and 4 to 6 late payments.

# Create a bar chart to visualize the customer count by state - rank your bars in a descending order
# We must remember that we have to use the order part in a sns.barplot and we will use "order=df.sort_values(column, ascending=False)"
descend = state_count.sort_values('customer_id', ascending=False).billing_state
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
sns.barplot(data=state_count,
              x='billing_state',
              y='customer_id',
              order=descend)
plt.title('Customer Count by State')
plt.xlabel('State')
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()
  • Here we have a barplot with State as our X variable and Count of the Customer ID as the Y variable. What we can see thanks to the descending order is that Alaska, Connecticut, New Jersey, Virginia, South Dakota are on top 5 States for doing business. They are really doing a great job and must have great promotions/services offered in these states. Now, we can also see that Alabama, Utah, Tennessee, and Wisconsin, and even California are the bottom states for customer count. This is quite suprising as California, Wisconsin and Tennessee would be expected to have a lot of business/customers but that does not seem to be the case. What we can include is that phone services/promotions are not good in these states.

# Matplot Lib Cross Tabulation, Stacked Bar Charts
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
# Sort the values in ascending order and we are sorting by False
ctab3.sort_values(False,inplace=True)
# -- check out bottom option, this stacks our bars.
plt.bar(x=ctab3['network_speed'],
        height=ctab3[True],
 			facecolor='lightblue', alpha=0.5, label="True")
plt.bar(x=ctab3['network_speed'],
        height=ctab3[False],
		    bottom=ctab3[True],     # bottom refers to the second height of the bar plot
             facecolor='red', alpha=0.5, label="False")
plt.title('Churn by Network Speed ')
plt.ylabel('Churn Percentage')
plt.xlabel('Network Speed')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Network Speed does not seem to influence Churn as the two stacked barplots are roughly similar in size and show that there is no difference in churning based on what Network Speed is being used. 4GLTE and 5G both high perfomring networking speeds, but there might be a huge difference in performance between the two, we could assume. The percentage for churning across both Network Speeds is roughly 5% or 0.05, so not very likely or playing a huge role.
